# Migrating `BackgroundProcessor` to .NET 8

## Key Breaking Change

**`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8.** The entire cancellation model must change.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask Stop(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (_workerTask != await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)))
        {
            // Log warning: worker did not exit within timeout
            // No forced kill equivalent — design so the token is always respected
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Issue | Detail |
|-------|--------|
| **`Thread.Abort()` gone** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. No replacement exists — you must use cooperative cancellation (`CancellationToken`). |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` gone** | Same — no `ThreadAbortException` is ever raised. |
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a synchronous I/O or `Monitor.Wait`, cancellation won't interrupt it. You must switch to async APIs that accept a `CancellationToken`. |
| **`volatile bool` race** | The original pattern has a race: the thread could start a new item after `_running = false`. `CancellationToken` fixes this — check it before *and* pass it into blocking work. |
| **No forced termination** | .NET 8 has **no safe equivalent** to `Thread.Abort()`. If third-party code doesn't respect tokens, your only escape hatch is running it in a **separate process** and killing that process. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in Stop** | Replace with `await Task.WhenAny` + timeout to avoid blocking the caller. |

## If You Can't Make `GetNextItem` Async

Wrap it so cancellation can still unblock the wait:

```csharp
private WorkItem GetNextItemCancellable(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Example: if backed by a BlockingCollection<T>
    _queue.TryTake(out var item, Timeout.Infinite, token);
    return item;
}
```

Or use `Task.Run` + token registration to abandon a truly uncooperative call (last resort — the thread leaks):

```csharp
var tcs = new TaskCompletionSource<WorkItem>();
using var reg = token.Register(() => tcs.TrySetCanceled());
var workTask = Task.Run(() => tcs.TrySetResult(GetNextItem()));
return await tcs.Task; // throws on cancel
```

## Summary

The migration is **not mechanical** — it requires redesigning the shutdown path around cooperative cancellation. Audit every blocking call in the loop and ensure it accepts and respects a `CancellationToken`.
